Falcon says while abortion is illegal, an economic crisis from 2008 to 2013 created unintended consequences. "Jobs became in scarce--people moved away," says Falcon. Women would often turn to abortion to enable themselves to leave the country. Doctors and midwives were left taking on this duty, but had no training or resources on how to safely provide abortions. Falcon says it was not associated with any political agenda, but rather was borne of desperation.

Falcon helped to develop a program called Belize Advocates for Reproductive Health (BARH). In 2009, the Justice 4 Women Organization in Belize City was trained to assist individuals in carrying UN drugs outside of Belize, who have been prescribed Misoprostol/prostaglandin to treat Cystic Ovarian Malignant Disease (COMD) in women in Belize who are in the early stages of pregnancy. Today, Misoprostol is still the method used by most women who have a private abortion in Belize City because of the limited resources and training of medical professionals in the public system. However, Falcon hopes that as awareness of these resources increases, more women will shy away from unsafe alternatives altogether.
